observations.recommendation:
We recommended, and Management agreed to direct the OCA to:

Revisit, validate and confirm the existence of long outstanding payable accounts in the books and if found non-existent, consider processing for reversion;

Verify the accounts under the five SLs with negative balances to determine the accuracy and existence of the balance;

Prepare adjusting journal entries to correct the noted errors;

Clarify and reestablish roles of the two concerned personnel on the preparation of JEV to eliminate double recording of transactions;

Moving forward, require the copy of the JEV when processing payments for transactions recorded previously as AP.

Prepare and maintain Index of Payments for each supplier to strengthen the control and monitoring of payments; and

Prepare and maintain SLs/schedules of outstanding APs per supplier to support the control account and for ease of monitoring of the balances due.

We recommended the Management direct the OCB to:

Include in the AB the breakdown of the LDRRMF per expense class and object of expenditure;

Properly maintain budget registries for each class expenditure of the LDRRMF;

Resolve the technical issues of the computerized budget system to match with the data in the RAAOs and other reports of the OCA; and

Continue to exert efforts to regularly reconcile the budgetary registries and required reports against the registries, reports and records maintained by the OCA and promptly resolve any discrepancies arising during the process.

We recommended, and Management agreed to direct:

The OCA to:

Prepare JEV to effect adjustments of the unrecorded immovable assets for CYs 2022 to 2023 in the books vis-à-vis RPCPPE amounting to ₱16.800 million;

Continuously exert effort on the cleansing of unreconciled variance of movable assets under SEF amounting to ₱10.559 million;

Continuously cleansing of unreconciled discrepancy of immovable assets amounting to ₱239.458 million;

Moving forward, ensure that cleansing set-up of PPE recognition does not include current year’s transactions as the same should be recognize in the books of accounts on the basis of appropriate supporting documents and not the data per physical count of PPE;

Derecognize or adjust respective PPE accounts for movable and immovable assets which are no longer owned by the City such as those donated to OGAs amounting to ₱3.643 million and ₱6.797 million;

Transfer the completed projects amounting to ₱8.014 million to its appropriate PPE accounts and adjust the CIP account duly supported by certificate of completion;

Revisit COA Circular No. 2015-009 for proper classification and disclosures of accounts in the FS and adjust posting errors under Immovable Assets amounting to ₱20.622 million. Likewise, for CIP accounts, recognize ongoing projects under its proper CIP accounts, moving forward;

Trace back prior years’ documents to come up with a reliable SL detail on CIP account under GF to completely support the same PPE account balances reflected in the FS; 

Provide the CGSO with a document indicating the expenses related to the acquisition of the noted parcels of land totalling ₱23.004 million per DOS to ensure uniform recognition of cost betrween the two offices, and to do the same for future acquisitions; and

Coordinate with the CGSO on the details of the ₱14.558 million increase in the land account to ensure consistent presentation in both offices.

The IC to:

Effect the necessary adjustments for unreported PPEs for CYs 2022 to 2023 totalling ₱281.174 million in the RPCPPE vis-à-vis SL;

Report the procured 25 Rescue Vehicles in the RPCPPE as of December 31, 2023 under Motor Vehicles account;

Report the completed projects amounting to ₱3.015 million in the RPCPPE;

Adjust the noted net overstatement of ₱21.613 million in the RPCPPE due to immovable assets that were recorded twice, variance in reporting of cost based on appropriation instead actual cost incurred, and turned-over projects; and

Continuously exert effort on the cleansing of movable and immovable assets accounts in the RPCPPE and coordinate with the OCA on the proper classification and disclosures of PPE accounts in the RPCPPE.

The CEO to:

Fast track the submission of Certificate of Completion, Certificate of Project Turn-over, and Certificate of Acceptance, if applicable, to the OCA for cleansing of PPE accounts particularly CIP accounts; and

Assist and coordinate with OCA on tracking back prior years’ data on the PPAs that are still lodged in the CIP SL and ensure timely submission and reporting of documents of completed projects to the latter for recording in the books of accounts.

The CGSO to:

 Coordinate with the OCA to ensure consistent capture of cost and details for the noted inconsistencies in the land properties of the City; and

Coordinate with the CEO to verify whether the noted road lots included in the Land property records are separate and distinct from those declared under the road lot component of the Road Network and proceed with effecting the adjustments, as may be necessary.

We further recommended, and Management agreed to intensify its policies and practices to address the noted deficiencies through proper coordination between several departments like the OCA, IC, CGSO, and CEO and proactively perform regular monitoring procedures to reconcile various inconsistencies discussed above.

We recommended, and management agreed to direct the OCA to:

Continuously exert effort in tracing back prior years’ records pertaining to the acquisition and/or recording of the various PPE accounts amounting to ₱718.022 million;

Effect the necessary adjustments for the recognition of the prior years’ depreciation and the corresponding accumulated depreciation of various PPE accounts amounting to ₱718.022 million, taking into consideration the cost, year, month of purchase/completion, and useful life. Thereafter, provide for the annual depreciation, if applicable;

Adjust the noted and overstatement of total accumulated depreciation and depreciation expenses of ₱48.157 million and ₱3.697 million in the books of accounts, respectively, and furnish JEV to COA Office;

Revisit Annex A of COA Circular No. 2003-007 and DPWH DO No. 176 s. 2015, and make necessary corrections on its depreciation schedule, for consistency on the EUL;

Carefully review computation of depreciation to avoid over and/or understatement of depreciation expenses, moving forward; and

Provide depreciation for completed projects that are still recorded in the books of account under SEF.

We recommended, and Management agreed to direct:

The OCA to Coordinate with the CGSO, and other concerned offices on the details of the 33.536 million Road Networks that have already been turned over to barangays to facilitate adjustment in the accounting books, and

The CGSO to coordinate with the OCA on the Road Network projects that have been turned-over to barangay LGUs to facilitate exclusion from the property records.

We recommended, and Management agreed to direct the OCA to prepare the JEV to reclassify the ₱2.950 million from the TF to be part of the road lot for Road Network.

We recommended, and Management agreed to direct:

The OCA to:

Determine the nature of the abnormal negative balance of 2.230 million and prepare JEV to adjust the same;

Compile and finalize the PPELCs to completely support the reported value of the Land in the FS;

Compile and finalize the Road Network Ledger Cards to completely support the reported value of the Road Network in the FS;

Compile and finalize the PPELCs of Immovable Assets, other than Land and Road Networks accounts, to completely support the same PPE items reflected in the FS;

Expedite efforts in reaching out to system providers in order to fix the technical issues regarding the information for Road Networks.

The CGSO to:

Compile and finalize the PCs for land to completely support the Land balance reflected in the RPCPPE;

Compile and update the local Road Network PCs to completely support the Road Network accounts balance reflected in the RPCPPE;

Compile and finalize the PCs of Immovable Assets, other than Land and Road Networks accounts, to completely support the same PPE items reflected in the RPCPPE;

Update and complete the PCs of Movable Assets to support the same PPE items replicated in the RPCPPE; and

Expedite efforts in obtaining Road Network ID Numbers for complete property records.

We recommended, and Management agreed to direct:

The OCA to:

Prepare the JEV to correct the erroneous recognition of inventory for the ₱477,500.00 reimbursement and to recognize the corresponding expense, and the erroneous recognition of inventory for the undelivered goods of ₱1.129 million;

Review the noted inconsistencies in the JEVs and their supporting documents, prepare correcting entry, if warranted, and provide explanation on the occurrence;

Coordinate with the CGSO on the inventory classification as recorded in the accounting books, and to reconcile the reported inventory with the RPCI; and

Coordinate with the CGSO to strategize and establish effective mechanisms in the preparation and submission of consolidated SSMI to the OCA to ensure timely recording in the books of accounts.

Validate the actual deliveries of goods recognized as accounts payable at year-end from the CGSO.

The CGSO to:

Coordinate with the OCA for the list of delivered goods still recognized as inventory and determine whether the same are still in stock. If otherwise, prepare SSMI and submit to OCA;

Instruct supply officers thru issuance of a memorandum to monitor the issuances of goods and preparation and submission within the prescribed period of SSMI to CGSO for consolidation, and update of stock cards;

Coordinate with the OCA in the reconciliation of the RPCI with the inventory balance in the FS; and

Establish an effective mechanism to ensure proper and timely reporting of supply and inventory issuances on all deliveries.

We recommended, and Management agreed to:

Craft internal control policies and procedures in the processing and monitoring of claims from PHIC; 

Adopt a computerized system integrating the component processes of both the hospital operations and PhilHealth billing and claims to shorten processing time, establish easily verifiable status of claims and reduce incidence of RTH and denied claims;

Install dedicated personnel responsible in the supervision, monitoring and control of personnel/process owners and activities/ workflow in the processing of claims from PhilHealth to ensure timely submission of claims and reduce, if not eliminate, returned and denied claims;

Consider providing additional trained personnel on a full-time basis to the Billing and Claims Section of the CCAH who shall be responsible in the gathering/ checking of documents to support the information in the CSFs and proper accomplishment thereof prior to transmittal of the claims to PHIC;

Henceforth, strictly comply with the mandatory date of filing of PhilHealth claims as prescribed in the IRR of the National Health Insurance Act of 2013.

Further, we recommended and Management agreed to direct the City Budget Officer to:

Include in the AB the breakdown of the LDRRMF per allotment class;

Properly maintain budget registries for each allotment class of the LDRRMF;

Resolve the technical issues of the computerized budget system to match with the data in the RAAOs and other reports of the OCA; and

Continue to exert efforts to regularly reconcile the budgetary registries and other required reports against the registries, reports and records maintained by the OCA, and promptly resolve any discrepancies arising during the process.

We recommended, and Management agreed to direct the OCA to:
Revisit, validate and confirm the existence of long outstanding payable accounts in the books and if found non-existent, consider processing for reversion;
Verify the accounts under the five SLs with negative balances to determine the accuracy and existence of the balance;
Prepare adjusting journal entries to correct the noted errors;
Clarify and reestablish the roles of the two concerned personnel on the preparation of JEV to eliminate the double recording of transactions;
Moving forward, require the copy of the JEV when processing payments for transactions recorded previously as Accounts Payable;
Prepare and maintain Index of Payments for each supplier to strengthen the control and monitoring of payments; and
Prepare and maintain SLs/schedules of outstanding APs per supplier to support the control account and for ease of monitoring of the balances due.

We recommended that Management direct the:

CE to strictly monitor the implementation of the Ordinance and enhance procedures to correct the above-noted gaps or deficiencies particularly in the delineation of the accountability and responsibility of the Port Manager-Designate in the process flow of the Citizen’s Charter;

Port Manager-Designate to stop the practice of billing per TL in equipment rental as this runs counter to the prescribed rates of fees provided in the SP Ordinance and refrain from issuing unauthorized slip of paper to the Cashier as neither the Ordinance nor the Citizen’s Charter provided him or his Office the authority to perform such function; 

The Cashier through the City Treasurer:

Require Billing Statement or its equivalent document or form approved by authorized personnel of the City Government and attach the same as supporting document to the RCDs; and

Double check or ensure that rates of fees for equipment rental are correctly applied;

The Motorpool In-charge to indicate in their billing statement or its equivalent document or form the type of equipment and fuel to be used including details on plate numbers and no. of liters of fuel to ensure proper accountability and accuracy of amount collected; and

The City Accountant to refrain from booking up prior year collections as current income and ensure that billing statement or its equivalent document is attached to the RCDs upon receipt of these reports from the City Treasurer.

2.13 We recommended that Management direct:
The CCAH to submit the RPCI of unaccounted inventories in Medical Supply Room and Pharmacy to the CGSO and OCA. For future related transactions, report all unused inventories as of year end in the RPCI;
The OCA to adjust the noted understatement and overstatement of inventories and expenses, respectively;
The CGSO to revise the consolidated RPCI and submit the same to COA and assign a property custodian for each office or department in the City to conduct semi-annual physical count of inventories and consolidate the same in the RPCI.
2.14 We also recommended that Management be consistent in the application of its accounting policy in the account Office Supplies Inventory for all departments.

5.6  We recommended that Management direct the City Accountant to:
Submit a written plan of action, which includes among others the timeline for the reconciliation of the accounts involved;
Review and reconcile the reciprocal accounts and  effect the necessary adjustments;
Establish clear-cut internal policies on the periodic reconciliation of accounts in order to eliminate the above noted differences in the accounts and prevent the same from recurrence.

13.9 We recommended that Management direct the Hospital Administrator-Designate and CHO to ensure that the:
Drugs and medicines indicated in the PR are in accordance with the DPRI. In cases where the prices of drugs and medicines procured are not listed in the DPRI, ensure that prior canvass/market survey has been made by the end-user;
Certification that the products fall within and conform with the latest edition of the PNF Manual is included as attachment when submitting PR to the BAC as required in DOH AO No 2016-0034;
PR includes shelf-life requirement of drugs and medicines; and
Technical specifications of drugs and medicines are completely indicated in the PRs.
13.10 We also recommended, and Management agreed to direct the BAC to:
Evaluate the prices of drugs and medicines in accordance with DPRI or market price as a result of prior canvass/survey in case prices are not found in DPRI, upon receipt of PR;
Include the necessary supporting documents mentioned in the preceding paragraphs from the suppliers and their respective offices, as required in DOH AO No. 2016-0034 and COA Circular 2012-002 in the procurement of drugs and medicines; and
Ensure that Price Form/Request for Quotations (RFQs) are complete with technical specifications of the drugs and medicines as indicated in the PRs.

17.11 We reiterated our recommendations that management direct the City Planning and Development Coordinator and City Engineer to adopt the following measures:
Provide timeline for every program/project and make sure that the timelines set are realistic and are strictly followed;
Fast track the implementation of those PPAs which have not yet been started and have remained unfinished as at year-end;
Ensure that approved suspension orders are supported by relevant certifications or supporting documents; and
Craft detailed project monitoring and evaluation guidelines not just to ensure accountability and completion of PPAs within the timelines set but also to institutionalize best practices and interventions for infrastructure and non-infrastructure projects.

Recommendations:
19.6 	We recommended that Management direct the:
CE to strictly monitor the implementation of the Ordinance and enhance procedures to correct the above-noted gaps or deficiencies particularly in the delineation of the accountability and responsibility of the Port Manager-Designate in the process flow of the Citizen’s Charter;
Port Manager-Designate to stop the practice of billing per TL in equipment rental as this runs counter to the prescribed rates of fees provided in the SP Ordinance and refrain from issuing unauthorized slip of paper to the Cashier as neither the Ordinance nor the Citizen’s Charter provided him or his Office the authority to perform such function;
The Cashier through the City Treasurer:
Require Billing Statement or its equivalent document or form approved by authorized personnel of the City Government and attach the same as supporting document to the RCDs; and
Double check or ensure that rates of fees for equipment rental are correctly applied;
The Motorpool In-charge to indicate in their billing statement or its equivalent document or form the type of equipment and fuel to be used including details on plate numbers and no. of liters of fuel to ensure proper accountability and accuracy of amount collected; and
The City Accountant to refrain from booking up prior year collections as current income and ensure that billing statement or its equivalent document is attached to the RCDs upon receipt of these reports from the City Treasurer.

11.12 	We recommended that the City Mayor require all concerned officials to revisit and    adhere strictly to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2013-004 dated January 30, 2013.
11.13 It is also recommended that the City Engineer:
Submit to COA, at the beginning of each year, the list of all ongoing government projects/programs/activities and those that are for implementation during the year;
Direct the City Engineer to inform COA that the appropriate signboards and/or public notices have already been posted within the prescribed period for validation; and
Fully update all data in their Monthly Monitoring Report to keep track of the progress of all PPAs within his power/jurisdiction from planning stage to implementation to completion since it is incumbent upon him as City Engineer of the LGU to “administer, coordinate, supervise, and control the construction, maintenance, improvement, repair of roads, bridges, and other engineering and public works projects of the local government unit concerned” pursuant to Section 477 of RA 7160.  Also, the CPDO shall be furnished with the said report as input to the required report of COA;

We recommended that Management:
Direct the CAO and CTO to:
1.    Exert effort to identify and verify the reconciling items and proceed with the recording and adjusting of the same in the books of accounts of the City, especially on the items with notable amount;
2.    Commit to perform a periodic reconciliation of the Treasurer’s Cashbook and of the Accounting Ledgers, to aid in the identification of material differences between their records, and arrive at a reliable CIB account balance;
Set-up control policies in order to prevent the accumulation of unadjusted reconciling items in the BRS.

We recommended that the CAO:
Regularly monitor the movement of the CAs of certain AOs in order to restrict granting of additional CAs to those with existing balances, as well as to better oversee the timely liquidation of the same;
Send demand letters, requiring the liquidation of CAs to the AOs concerned and effect the necessary sanctions for failure to liquidate the same;
Continue to monitor compliance with the requirements for the write-off of the unliquidated CAs of the deceased officers and employees of the City;
Prepare the necessary adjusting entries, wherever appropriate, regarding the existing negative balances of some AOs, and henceforth limit the recording of the liquidation to the amount of cash advanced to avoid having negative balances.

We recommended that management:
Carefully plan and review PPAs to be included in the AIP, set specific and realistic timeline for every program/project based on approved POW and specify cost of each program/project in order to avoid lump sum allocation;
Review the AIP and Status of Appropriations, Allotments and Obligations (SAAO) from CYs 2013 to 2018 to determine what PPAs are still to be implemented and fast track their implementation;
Instead of implementation of infrastructure projects by administration, consider mode of implementation by contract to reduce the substantial number of unimplemented projects of the City;
Prepare APPs that are duly linked to AIP to ensure that every procurement is cost efficient and effective and conforms with RA 9184;
Refrain from spending more than the appropriated amount for each program/project;
Invest in high-impact capital expenditure projects in the utilization of 20% DF and refrain from proposing non-capital investment projects under the fund;
Prioritize close coordination among offices concerned especially in submitting reports, data and the like to facilitate transactions, reconciled and accurate financial reports/documents; and
Adhere with Sections 276 and 277 of RA 7160 on the separation of duties of the CPDO and CEO.

We recommend that Management direct the:
City Assessor’s Office to initiate and coordinate with other involved offices to fast track the implementation of the revised Schedule of FMVs per Ordinance No. 18-286;
City Assessor’s Office to include in their CY 2019 schedule the activities necessary for faster implementation of the revised Schedule of FMVs, including the identification of idle lands to allow prompt implementation of the additional provision;
CTO to evaluate the reasons on the decrease of collections and formulate plans and activities to encourage higher collections for the succeeding years;
Offices of the City Treasurer and City Assessor to bring to the attention of the computer specialist or programmer about the flaws in the electronic system currently used so that these can be addressed.

We recommended that the City Accountant:
Continuously send demand letters requi-ring the liquidation of CAs to the accountable officers concerned and effect the necessary sanctions upon failure to liquidate the same;
Make the necessary adjusting entries, wherever appropriate, regarding the existing negative balances of some accountable officers;
Reclassify Advances to Officers and Employees of ₱2,955,190.00 to Advances to SDOs to better reflect the nature of the transaction, and;
Process the write-off of the unliquidated CAs of the deceased officers and employees of the City.


We further recommended that the personnel in charge of the pre-audit of cash advances regularly monitor the movement of the CAs of certain AOs, to restrict the granting of additional CAs as well as to better oversee the timely liquidation of the same.

We recommended that management:
Require the CEO to explain the reason why projects were not completed within the timeframe;
Require the Accounting Office in coordination with the CEO to reconcile the discrepancy of ₱5,323,752.10 noted between the Monthly Project Status Report and SAAOB;
Review the AIP from CYs 2013 to 2017 to determine the PPAs that are still to be implemented and fast track their implementation especially for PPAs under the BUB program, the fund releases of which have limited period of validity; 
Review current manpower requirements of the City vis-à-vis unimplemented PPAs.  If in-house capability is not adequate to implement PPAs as scheduled, consider mode of implementation by contract for projects of substantial estimated project costs especially those where the target completion dates and/or year of implementation, have already lapsed; and
Strengthen the conduct of proper planning and timely execution, as well as continuous monitoring and evaluation of PPAs to address issues that may be needed to be resolved during their implementation.


We recommended that management:
Require the BuB focal person to prepare and submit the required reports to the Regional Poverty Reduction Action Team (PRAT) concerned to avoid sanctions by donor agencies;
Require the Head, City Planning and Development Office to include in the AIP, all BuB projects to be implemented during the year;
Require the CGSO or the concerned Office to render a report on the Sta. Isabel Day Care Center which was razed to the ground by fire for purposes of supporting request for relief from accountability for its loss;
Require the BAC to invite at least three Local Poverty Reduction Action Plan (LPRAP) signatories to biddings conducted on the purchase of materials and/or services for BuB projects and advise the BAC to adopt shopping only if the conditions as stated in RA 9184 are present;
Require the BuB focal person to follow up and obtain completely signed MOAs, which henceforth, are to be prepared, signed and specify the details relative to projects to be undertaken;
Require the DSWD and DA personnel to specify the sub-projects for which materials are used, and to support vouchers with training modules and the barangays for which trainings or projects are undertaken; and
Require the proponents of proposed BuB projects to conduct thorough planning in coming up with project proposals, and consultations with residents to be affected by the implementation of said projects.


We recommended that the Planning, Engineering, Treasury, Accounting, CSWD and other concerned divisions/ offices coordinate efforts to fast track the implementation of BuB projects to benefit the City’s grassroots population and that management require the BuB focal person to regularly monitor the status of proposed BuB projects as to funding and implementation.


We recommended that management:
Direct the Office of the City Accountant to submit the Year-End Financial Statements and supporting schedules including the remaining reports and other financial documents for CY 2017. 
Consider hiring additional personnel for the Accounting Office and ensure proper division of the workload amongst them. 
Personnel involved in the preparation of reports be properly briefed about the new system.
All offices and personnel involved in the preparation of the LDRRMF Utilization Report coordinate and set their own deadlines so that this report will be submitted on a monthly basis and within 15 days after the close of each month pursuant with Section 5.1.5 of COA Circular 2012-002.


We recommended that the City Mayor:
Issue an Order directing the City Planning and Development Coordinator (CPDC) to lead the preparation and submission to COA of the QR on Gov’t PPAs considering that it is one of his duties to monitor and evaluate the implementation of the different development PPAs in the LGU concerned pursuant with the approved development plan;
Direct the CEO to fully update all data in the Monthly Monitoring Report (MMR) to keep track of the progress of all PPAs within his power/ jurisdiction from the planning stage to implementation thru completion since it is incumbent upon the CEO of the LGU to “administer, coordinate, supervise, and control the construction, maintenance, improvement, repair of roads, bridges, and other engineering and public works projects of the local government unit concerned” pursuant to Section 477 of RA 7160.  The CPDC should be furnished with the said report as input to the required report of COA;
Direct the Project Heads/Managers of all non-infrastructure PPAs to prepare and maintain a MMR for submission to the Office of the CPDC; 
Direct the CEO and Project Heads/Managers to coordinate with the City Accountant on the costs incurred of the projects for inclusion in their respective MMR; and
Require all concerned officials to adhere to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2013-004.

We recommended that the City Accountant:
Continuously send demand letters requiring the liquidation of cash advances to the accountable officers concerned and effect the necessary sanctions upon failure to liquidate the same;
Make the necessary adjusting entries, wherever appropriate, regarding the existing negative balances of some accountable officers;
Reclassify Advances to Officers and Employees of ₱2,955,190.00 to Advances to Special Disbursing Officers to better reflect the nature of the transaction, and;
Process the write-off of the unliquidated cash advances of the deceased officers and employees of the City.
We further recommended that the personnel in charge of the pre-audit of cash advances regularly monitor the movement of the cash advances of certain accountable officers, to restrict the granting of additional cash advances as well as to better oversee the timely liquidation of the same.

We recommended that management:
Require the CEO to explain the reason why projects were not completed within the timeframe;
Require the Accounting Office in coordination with the CEO to reconcile the discrepancy of ₱5,323,752.10 noted between the MPSR and SAAOB;
Review the Annual Investment Plan from CYs 2013 to 2017 to determine the PPAs that are still to be implemented and fast track their implementation especially for PPAs under the BUB program, the fund releases of which have limited period of validity;
Review current manpower requirements of the City vis-à-vis unimplemented PPAs.  If in-house capability is not adequate to implement PPAs as scheduled, consider mode of implementation by contract for projects of substantial estimated project costs especially those where the target completion dates and/or year of implementation, have already lapsed; and
Strengthen the conduct of proper planning and timely execution of PPAs as well as continuous monitoring and evaluation of PPAs in order to address issues that may be needed to be resolved during their implementation.

We recommended that the City Mayor:
Issue an Order directing the City Planning and Development Coordinator to lead the preparation and submission to COA of the Quarterly Report on Government PPAs considering that it is one of his duties to monitor and evaluate the implementation of the different development PPAs in the LGU concerned in accordance with the approved development plan;
Direct the City Engineer to fully update all data in the Monthly Monitoring Report (MMR) to keep track of the progress of all PPAs within his power/jurisdiction from the planning stage to implementation thru completion since it is incumbent upon him as City Engineer of the LGU to “administer, coordinate, supervise, and control the construction, maintenance, improvement, repair of roads, bridges, and other engineering and public works projects of the local government unit concerned” pursuant to Section 477 of RA 7160.  The CPDC should be furnished with the said report as input to the required report of COA;
Direct the Project Heads/Managers of all non-infrastructure PPAs to prepare and maintain a Monthly Monitoring Report for submission to the Office of the CPDC;
Direct the City Engineer and Project Heads/Managers to coordinate with the City Accountant on the costs incurred of the projects for inclusion in their respective Monthly Monitoring Report; and
Require all concerned officials to adhere strictly to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2013-004.

Recommendation:


    We recommended that management:

   1. Require the BuB focal  person  to  prepare  and  submit  the  required reports to the RPRAT/s concerned to avoid sanctions by donor agencies;


   2. Require the Head, City Planning and Development Office to  include  in the AIP, all BuB projects to be implemented during the year;

   3. Require the CGSO or the concerned Office to render  a  report  on  the Sta. Isabel day care center which was razed to the ground by fire  for purposes of supporting request for relief from accountability for  its loss;
   4. Require the BAC to invite at least three LPRAP signatories to biddings conducted on  the  purchase  of  materials  and/or  services  for  BuB projects;


   5. Advise the BAC to adopt shopping only if the conditions as  stated  in RA 9184 are present;


   6. Require the BuB focal person to follow up and obtain completely signed MOAs. Henceforth, the MOAs that are to be prepared and  signed  should  specify the details relative to projects to be undertaken;

   7. Require the DSWD and  Department  of  Agriculture  (DA)  personnel  to specify the sub-projects for which  materials are used, and to support vouchers with  training modules and the barangays for which  trainings or projects are undertaken; and


   8. Require the proponents of proposed BuB projects  to  conduct  thorough planning in coming up with project proposals, and  consultations  with residents to be affected by the implementation of said projects.
